# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: worcester-worcesters
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:worcester-worcesters/1880-worcester-worcesters-season] The 1880 season was the first for the **Worcester Worcesters** franchise in the National League, having played 1879 in the National Association.
[src:worcester-worcesters/1880-worcester-worcesters-season] The team finished its initial season with a 40–43 record, good for fifth place.
[src:worcester-worcesters/1880-worcester-worcesters-season] Lee Richmond threw a perfect game on June 12, 1880, the first ever perfect game in Major League Baseball history in a 1–0 victory over the Cleveland Blues.
[src:worcester-worcesters/1880-worcester-worcesters-season] On August 20, they became the first major-league team to be no-hit at home when Pud Galvin of the Buffalo Bisons defeated them, 1–0.
[src:worcester-worcesters/1881-worcester-worcesters-season] The **1881 Worcester Worcesters** finished with a 32–50 record, last place in the National League.
[src:worcester-worcesters/1882-worcester-worcesters-season] The **1882 Worcester Worcesters** finished with an 18–66 record, last place in the National League.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-association-19th-century] The **American Association of Base Ball Clubs** (**AA**) was a professional baseball league that existed for 10 seasons from 1882 to 1891.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-association-19th-century] Together with the National League (NL), founded in 1876, the AA participated in an early version of the World Series seven times versus the champion of the NL in an interleague championship playoff tournament.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-association-19th-century] At the end of its run, several AA franchises joined the NL.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-association-19th-century] After 1891, the NL existed alone, with each season's champions being awarded the Temple Cup (1894–1897).
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-association-19th-century] During its existence, the AA was often simply referred to as "the Association" in the media, in contrast to the NL, which was sometimes called "the League".
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-association-19th-century] It was also sometimes called the "Beer and Whiskey League".
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-association-19th-century] The American Association (AA) distinguished itself in several ways from what it considered to be the puritanical National League (NL).
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-association-19th-century] The new league established teams in what the NL leaders pejoratively called "river cities", including Pittsburgh, Cincinnati, Louisville and St.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-association-19th-century] Louis, with the inherent implication of lower morality or social standards in those cities.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-association-19th-century] In contrast to the NL, the AA offered cheaper ticket prices, Sunday games and alcoholic beverages to its patrons.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-association-19th-century] On November 8, 1881, at the Gibson House in Cincinnati, it was decided that individual teams in the league-to-be would operate their own affairs and set their own admission prices, under an agreement called the "guarantee system".
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-association-19th-century] The NL at that time prohibited the sale of alcohol on its grounds, while the AA had no such restrictions, especially as several of its teams were backed by breweries and distilleries.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-association-19th-century] The AA became known as "The Beer and Whiskey League", another pejorative term applied by NL owners, which did not seem to bother the fans of the Association's clubs.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-association-19th-century] Beginning in 1884 and continuing through 1890, the champion of the AA met the champion of the NL in an early version of the World Series.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-association-19th-century] These early Series were less organized than the modern version, with as few as three games played and as many as fifteen, and the contests of 1885 and 1890 ending in disputed ties.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-association-19th-century] The NL won four of these Series, while the AA won only one, in 1886 when the St.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-association-19th-century] Louis Cardinals) defeated the Chicago White Stockings (now the Chicago Cubs).
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-association-19th-century] Over its lifetime, the AA was weakened by several factors.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-association-19th-century] One was the tendency of some of its teams to jump to the NL.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-association-19th-century] The consistently stronger NL was in better position to survive adverse conditions.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-association-19th-century] Some owners of AA teams also owned a NL team.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-association-19th-century] The most significant blow to the AA was dealt by the Players' League, a third major league formed in 1890, which siphoned off talent and gate receipts.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-association-19th-century] In a rare historical oddity, the Brooklyn Bridegrooms (now the Los Angeles Dodgers) won the league's championship and represented the AA in the 1889 World Series, switched to the NL during the off-season, and then repeated the same feat.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-association-19th-century] No player who spent the majority of his career in the AA is in the baseball Hall of Fame, although Bid McPhee of the Cincinnati Reds played eight of his eighteen seasons in the AA before the Reds moved to the National League.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-association-19th-century] The living legacy of the old Association is the group of teams that came over to the National League to stay.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-association-19th-century] The Pirates moved to the NL after the 1886 season, the Bridegrooms/Dodgers and the Cincinnati Reds after the 1889 season, and the Browns/Cardinals after the American Association folded following the 1891 season.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-association-19th-century] Following the reorganization and contraction of the NL from 12 teams down to 8 in 1900, half of the eight surviving teams were former members of the AA.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-association-19th-century] Several of the AA's home-field venues survived into the 1960s: The ballpark used by the 1891 Washington club evolved into Griffith Stadium; the home of the St.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-association-19th-century] Louis Browns, Sportsman's Park; and the city block occupied by the Reds, which evolved into Crosley Field.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-association-19th-century] Other than the clubs themselves, Crosley Field was the last physical remnant of the AA—it was the home field of the Cincinnati Reds until mid-season 1970 and was razed in April 1972.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-association-19th-century] During the AA's existence, four clubs defected over to the NL: Allegheny City (joined NL 1887, later became the Pittsburgh Pirates), the Cleveland Spiders (joined NL 1889), the Brooklyn Bridegrooms (joined NL 1890, eventually renamed the Dodgers), and the Cincinnati Reds (joined NL 1890).
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-association-19th-century] At the AA's demise in 1891, four additional clubs joined the NL: the St.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-association-19th-century] Louis Browns (later the Cardinals), the Louisville Colonels, the Washington Statesmen (renamed the Senators), and the Baltimore Orioles.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-association-19th-century] Therefore, from 1892 to 1899, when the NL consisted of 12 teams, 8 of them had been former AA clubs.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-association-19th-century] All four have posted more than 10,000 all-time major-league victories.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-association-19th-century] AA statistics are recognized by Major League Baseball (MLB), the AA being one of six leagues deemed "major" by the Special Baseball Records Committee of Major League Baseball in 1969.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-association-19th-century] The first line is the formation of the American Association (AA) in 1882, and the second marks the end of the American Association.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-association-19th-century] World's Championship Series championships are shown with a "•", American Association Pennants in non-World Championship Series seasons are shown with a "#", and American Association Pennant winners who tied or lost the World Championship Series are shown with a "^".
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-association-19th-century] For the 1891 season, the Philadelphia Athletics were replaced by the Philadelphia Quakers of the Player's League.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-association-19th-century] The 1891 Cincinnati Kelly's Killers folded during the season and were replaced by the Milwaukee Brewers.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-association-19th-century] All non-American Association labels not labeled "NL" (National League) or "PL" (Players' League) are minor league teams.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-central] The **American League Central** is one of Major League Baseball's six divisions.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-central] This division was formed in the realignment of 1994 by moving three teams from the American League West and two teams from the American League East.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-central] Its teams are all located in the Midwestern United States.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-central] Along with the National League East, the AL Central is one of two divisions in the Major Leagues in which all of its members have won a World Series title.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-central] In fact, each team has captured at least two World Series championships.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-central] The Kansas City Royals were the most recent team from the division to win the World Series.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-central] The Cleveland Guardians were known as the Cleveland Indians until November 2021.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-central] The Chicago White Sox and Kansas City Royals are the only teams from the AL Central division to have won the World Series since the league realignment in 1994.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-central] In 1994, the Cleveland Indians were sitting atop the wild-card standings and would have qualified for the postseason as the AL's first wild card but on August 12 of that year, the season came to an early end due to a players strike, cancelling the remainder of the regular season and postseason.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-central] The 2006 Detroit Tigers were the first team from the Central to qualify as the wild card.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-central] MLB revamped the postseason starting in 2012, creating a new single-game playoff where two wildcards competed against each other while the division winners each received a bye.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-central] The winner of the American League wild card game moved on to face the top-seeded team of the AL in the American League Division Series.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-central] In 2013, the Indians became the first team from the AL Central to qualify as a wild card under the new postseason format.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-central] In 2014, the Kansas City Royals ended a 29-year postseason drought returning to the playoffs for the first time since winning the World Series in 1985.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-central] In 2020 only, eight teams, including the three division winners, played in a best-of-three Wild Card Series, with the winners advancing to the Division Series.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-central] Starting in 2022, the Wild Card field was increased to three teams, and along with the lowest-ranked division winner, qualified for the best-of-three Wild Card Series to determine the remaining two slots in the Division Series.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-central] † – Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, the season was shortened to 60 games.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-central] The White Sox were tied with the Cleveland Indians but lost the runner-up honors due to an inferior head-to-head record (White Sox lost the season series 2–8 to the Indians).
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-central] (**) The Tigers and Royals were tied for the 2nd Wild Card spot, but the Royals earned the tiebreaker by virtue of winning the regular season series 7–6.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-central] (***) Finished with the same record as the Houston Astros, but won the third wild-card spot due to the Tigers winning the season series 4–2.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-central] Totals updated through conclusion of the 2024 postseason.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-east] The **American League East** is one of Major League Baseball's six divisions.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-east] MLB consists of an East, Central, and West division for each of its two 15-team leagues, the American League (AL) and National League (NL).
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-east] This division was created before the start of the 1969 season along with the American League West.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-east] Before that time, each league consisted of 10 teams without any divisions.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-east] Four of the division's five teams are located in the Eastern United States, with the other team, the Toronto Blue Jays, in Eastern Canada.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-east] It is currently the only division that contains a non-American team.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-east] At the end of the Major League Baseball season, the team with the best record in the division earns one of the AL's six playoff spots.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-east] Baseball writers have long posited that the American League East is the toughest division in MLB; during its 50-year existence, an AL East team has gone on to play in the World Series 28 times, and 16 of those teams have been crowned World Series champions.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-east] Since the 1995 season, when the wild-card playoff berth was introduced, the AL East has produced 20 of the 32 wild-card teams for the American League, with the AL West sending seven teams, and only five coming from the AL Central.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-east] When MLB split into divisions for the 1969 season, the American League, unlike the National League, split its 12 teams strictly on geography.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-east] The six teams then located in the Eastern Time Zone were all placed in the AL East, with the other six teams making up the AL West.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-east] In September 1971, American League owners approved the move of the second Washington Senators franchise to Arlington, Texas, to become the Texas Rangers.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-east] With the Rangers moving to the AL West, the owners then debated whether the Chicago White Sox or Milwaukee Brewers should move to the AL East for 1972.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-east] The White Sox requested they be moved to the East under the argument of being an original AL franchise and playing most of their longtime rival teams, of which five were in the East.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-east] The Oakland Athletics (formerly from Kansas City and Philadelphia) objected to moving the White Sox to the East; owner Charlie Finley was a Chicago native who wanted to continue to make three trips per season with his club to the Second City.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-east] The Twins also argued that the National Football League's Dallas Cowboys played (and still do play) in the NFC East despite being far from the Northeast.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-east] The White Sox' pleas notwithstanding, the Brewers, who began as the Seattle Pilots in 1969 and had to endure long divisional road trips to Oakland and Anaheim (and vice-versa) in the AL West, were moved to the AL East.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-east] ; the Milwaukee Brewers moved to the AL East to maintain an equal number of teams in each division.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-east] , becoming the seventh team of the AL East.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-east] while Detroit moved to the AL Central, maintaining the AL East at five teams.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-east] Entering the 2008 season, Tampa Bay's team name changed from Devil Rays to Rays.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-east] † – Due to the 1981 Major League Baseball strike, the season was split.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-east] The Yankees won the first half and defeated the second-half champion Brewers (62–45) in the postseason.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-east] †† – Due to the 1994–95 Major League Baseball strike starting August 12, the season was not played to completion.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-east] The Yankees were leading at the time of the strike.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-east] + – The Red Sox and Yankees finished tied for first place with identical records.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-east] The Yankees were declared division winners, due to having won the season series against the Red Sox, and the Red Sox received the wild card berth.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-east] ††† – Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, the 2020 season was shortened to 60 games.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-east] By virtue of an expanded eight-team postseason format, the division runner-up Yankees also qualified for the playoffs.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-east] ++ – The Blue Jays and Yankees finished tied for first place with identical records.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-east] The Blue Jays were declared division winners, due to having won the season series against the Yankees, and the Yankees received the first wild card berth.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-east] Since the advent of the Wild Card, AL East teams have faced each other in the ALCS 5 times, the ALDS 4 times, and the Wild Card twice.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-east] Beginning in 2022, the postseason has expanded to three division leaders and three wild cards per league.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-west] The **American League West** is one of Major League Baseball's six divisions.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-west] The division has five teams as of the 2013 season, but had four teams from 1994 to 2012, and had as many as seven teams before the 1994 realignment.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-west] Although its teams currently only reside along the West Coast and in Texas, historically the division has had teams as far east as Chicago and Minnesota.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-west] From 1998 (when the NL West expanded to five teams) to 2012, the AL West was the only MLB division with four teams.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-west] The six teams located in the Eastern Time Zone were all placed in the AL East, and the remaining six were placed in the AL West.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-west] When the second incarnation of the Washington Senators announced their intention to move to the Dallas–Fort Worth area for the 1972 season and become the Texas Rangers, American League owners voted to switch the Rangers with the Milwaukee Brewers, who began as the Seattle Pilots in 1969.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-west] The Chicago White Sox asked the AL to move from West to East, citing that five of the original eight American League franchises were in the East.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-west] The Oakland Athletics and Minnesota Twins objected to the White Sox' request; the Twins also did not want the Brewers to leave the West.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-west] In 2013, the Houston Astros went from the National League Central to the AL West.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-west] That move gives all six MLB divisions an equal five teams and both leagues an equal 15 teams each.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-west] Place cursor over year for division champion or World Series team.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-west] Creation of division due to 1969 expansion, Kansas City and Seattle added.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-west] Seattle franchise moved to Milwaukee, becoming the Brewers.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-west] Seattle added in the 1977 league expansion.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-west] In 1997, California Angels become Anaheim Angels.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-west] In 2005, Anaheim Angels become Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-west] In 2016, Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim become Los Angeles Angels.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-west] in 2025, and dropped a location moniker.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-west] † – Due to the players' strike, the season was split in two.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-west] The Athletics won the first half and defeated the second-half winner, the Kansas City Royals, to win the division. § – Due to the 1994–95 Major League Baseball strike, starting on August 12, no official winner was declared.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-west] The Texas Rangers were leading in winning percentage at time of the strike.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-west] * – Seattle defeated the California Angels in a one-game playoff for the division title, 9–1. †† – Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, the season was shortened to 60 games.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-west] By virtue of the eight-team postseason format used for that season, division runner-up Houston also qualified for the playoffs.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-west] ** – The Astros and Rangers finished tied for first place with identical records.
[src:worcester-worcesters/american-league-west] The Astros were declared division winners, due to having won the season series against the Rangers, and the Rangers received the wild card berth.
[src:worcester-worcesters/worcester-worcesters] The **Worcester Worcesters** were a 19th-century Major League Baseball team from 1880 to 1882 in the National League.
[src:worcester-worcesters/worcester-worcesters] The team is referred to, at times, as the **Brown Stockings** or the **Ruby Legs**; however, no contemporary sources from the time exist that support the use of either name.
[src:worcester-worcesters/worcester-worcesters] The team played their home games at the Worcester Driving Park Grounds in the Worcester Agricultural Fairgrounds, located south of Highland Street between Sever Street and Russell Street in Worcester, Massachusetts.
[src:worcester-worcesters/worcester-worcesters] In 1879, Worcester played in the National Association, a league consisting of teams in the Northeast.
[src:worcester-worcesters/worcester-worcesters] The National League was interested in Worcester as a potential replacement for the failed Syracuse Stars franchise primarily based on the performance of their ace pitcher, Lee Richmond, who pitched several exhibition games against National League opponents and went 6–2.
[src:worcester-worcesters/worcester-worcesters] He also pitched and won one game for the Boston Red Stockings.
[src:worcester-worcesters/worcester-worcesters] To admit Worcester to the National League, the league's board of directors waived the requirement that league cities have a population of at least 75,000 (Worcester's population was 58,000).
[src:worcester-worcesters/worcester-worcesters] In December 1879, Worcester became the first professional baseball team to visit Cuba.
[src:worcester-worcesters/worcester-worcesters] The trip was a financial failure, as they were only able to play two games against Cuban teams.
[src:worcester-worcesters/worcester-worcesters] On June 12, 1880, Lee Richmond threw the first perfect game in Major League history, against the Cleveland Blues.
[src:worcester-worcesters/worcester-worcesters] A monument to the perfect game stands on the grounds of the Becker School of Design & Technology of Clark University at 61 Sever Street in Worcester.
[src:worcester-worcesters/worcester-worcesters] The team made history again on August 20 of the same year, by becoming the first team to be no-hit at home, when Pud Galvin of the Buffalo Bisons defeated them 1–0.
[src:worcester-worcesters/worcester-worcesters] In his 1948 book, *The Cincinnati Reds* (published by Putnam), Allen took some satisfaction in pointing out that the Reds re-formed in 1882, initially as a member of the American Association, the same year that Worcester's days as a major league franchise, as well as their influence, came to an end.
[src:worcester-worcesters/worcester-worcesters] Worcester proved to be too small to support a major league club; the team was encouraged to finish out its schedule as a lame duck before voluntarily resigning from the league.
[src:worcester-worcesters/worcester-worcesters] Their last two games of the season against the Troy Trojans, which also resigned from the NL for the same reasons, drew only 6 and 25 fans respectively; the attendance of six is a record low attendance for all league games open to spectators.
[src:worcester-worcesters/worcester-worcesters] The Worcester club formally tendered its resignation to the National League at the circuit's annual meeting in Providence on December 6, 1882.
[src:worcester-worcesters/worcester-worcesters] The club was placed on the league's roll of honorary membership.
[src:worcester-worcesters/worcester-worcesters] Needing an eighth team to balance the schedule, the National League granted an expansion franchise to Philadelphia, known as the Philadelphia Quakers.
[src:worcester-worcesters/worcester-worcesters] This team would evolve into the Philadelphia Phillies (a name used interchangeably with Quakers until 1890).
[src:worcester-worcesters/worcester-worcesters] Many sources, including the Phillies themselves, suggest that the Worcester club was moved to Philadelphia; however, only Worcester's former NL spot was moved.
[src:worcester-worcesters/worcester-worcesters] There is no direct link between the two teams, since Worcester resigned from the National League, and the franchise was not sold and moved to Philadelphia.
[src:worcester-worcesters/worcester-worcesters] One of the items on the agenda at the December 1882 annual meeting was whether to award new franchises to New York and Philadelphia.
[src:worcester-worcesters/worcester-worcesters] Further, no players from the 1882 Worcester club played for the Philadelphia team in 1883.
